\begin{abstract}
The phenomenon commonly referred to as ``morning wood''---technically nocturnal penile tumescence (NPT)---has long invited folk explanations ranging from sexual readiness to the need to urinate. 
This short review synthesises contemporary research on the physiological control of NPT, its putative adaptive value in human evolution, and its hydrodynamic consequences for urination.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Healthy adult males experience 3--5 spontaneous erections per night, the last of which often coincides with awakening.
Although usually benign, the event is clinically informative and evolutionarily puzzling.
Here we examine (i) neural and hormonal mechanisms driving NPT, (ii) hypotheses on its adaptive significance, and (iii) whether an erect penis truly increases urinary range (spoiler: mostly angle, not thrust).

\section{Physiological Mechanisms}
During rapid eye movement (REM) sleep the sympathetic tone falls and parasympathetic outflow triggers nitric--oxide mediated vasodilation of the corpora cavernosa.
Concurrently, circulating testosterone peaks at dawn, enhancing smooth--muscle relaxation.
The internal urethral sphincter closes via sympathetic \(\alpha\)-adrenergic action to prevent retrograde ejaculation, incidentally impeding urine flow.

\subsection{Role of the Bladder}
A distended bladder can reflexively promote erection via sacral afferents, but cystometric studies show this is neither necessary nor sufficient: NPT persists after catheterisation that eliminates bladder stretch.

\section{Evolutionary Perspectives}
\subsection{Tissue Oxygenation Hypothesis}
Nightly erections oxygenate cavernosal tissue, preventing fibrosis and preserving erectile capacity well into middle age---a direct boost to lifetime reproductive success.

\subsection{Readiness-at-Dawn Hypothesis}
In Pleistocene multi-male groups, males awakening ``pre-loaded'' could initiate copulation before rivals, leveraging the synchronous female oestrus at first light.

\subsection{Territorial Urination Hypothesis}
Distance--marking by urine is common in canids and felids.  However, NPT is phylogenetically conserved in mammals that do \emph{not} scent-mark, and uroflowmetry demonstrates reduced flow rates during erection.  
Therefore the hypothesis is unsupported.

\section{Fluid Dynamics of Urination with an Erection}
Ideal projectile range is
\[
R=\frac{v^{2}\sin 2\theta}{g},
\]
where \(v\) is exit velocity, \(\theta\) the angle relative to horizontal and \(g\) gravitational acceleration.  

Uroflow studies report slightly \emph{lower} \(v\) when the urethra is compressed during erection, but \(\theta\) typically increases from \(-20^{\circ}\) (flaccid) to \(40^{\circ}\) (erect).  
A purely geometric shift from \(20^{\circ}\) to \(45^{\circ}\) raises \(R\) by about 55\% even if \(v\) is unchanged, accounting for anecdotal reports of ``longer range''.

\section{Discussion}
The small metabolic cost and low risk of NPT allow even modest benefits---maintenance of erectile tissue and dawn mating advantage---to suffice for evolutionary retention.  
The ``pee farther'' story lacks both mechanical and fitness support.

\section{Conclusion}
NPT is best viewed as a multi-purpose maintenance and readiness routine rather than a hydraulic aid for micturition.
Its presence remains a convenient home test of neurovascular health.

\section*{References}
\begin{enumerate}
\item A. Stuckey and R. Walsh. \emph{Nocturnal penile tumescence: physiology and clinical utility}. J.~Urol. \textbf{198}, 2021.
\item L. Andersen et al. \emph{Circadian testosterone variation and sexual behaviour}. Horm.~Behav. \textbf{115}, 2019.
\item S. Sangiorgi et al. \emph{Uroflowmetry during nocturnal erections demonstrates reduced flow despite increased penile angle}. Neurourol.~Urodyn. \textbf{40}, 2021.
\item J. Dixson. \emph{Primate Sexuality: Comparative Studies of the Prosimians, Monkeys, Apes, and Humans}. Oxford Univ.\ Press, 2015.
\end{enumerate}

